ury, Cheshire, England","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"before 1062–":"before 1062–Deceased","1062–Male":"1062–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1094–1157":"1094–1157","1010–1067":"1010–1067","1010–Female":"1010–Deceased","1106":"1106","1157":"1157","1067":"1067","1066":"1066","1010":"1010","before 1062":"before 1062","1086":"1086","1030":"1030","1096":"1096","1062":"1062","before 1094":"before 1094","1094":"1094","Haughton, Bunbury Par, Cheshire, England":"Haughton, Cheshire, England","Bunbury, Cheshire, England":"Bunbury, Cheshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bird","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: nickname for a young or a small and slender person, from Middle English <i>brid</i>, <i>bird</i>, <i>burd</i> (Old English <i>bird</i>, <i>brid</i>, perhaps also <i>byrd</i>) ‘bird, young bird’, also ‘young man, young woman, child’.","Irish: Anglicized form of a number of Irish names erroneously thought to contain the element <i>éan</i> ‘bird’, in particular <i>Ó hÉinigh</i> (see   Heagney  ), <i>Ó hÉanna</i> (see   Heaney  ), <i>Ó hÉanacháin</i> (see   Heneghan  ), and <i>Mac an Déaghanaigh</i> (see   McEneaney  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of various European surnames meaning ‘bird’, as for example German and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Vogel  , French   Loiseau  , Czech <b>Ptáček</b> (see   Ptacek  ) and <b>Pták</b>, Polish   Ptak  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Kingbird","meanings":["Native American (Chippewa; also <b>King Bird</b>): translation into English of the Chippewa personal name <i>Ogimaa-bines(i)</i>, meaning literally ‘the bird that is king’ and referring to the mythological bird-like creature thunderbird. See also   Bird   4.","History: The progenitor of the large family of the Kingbirds from the Red Lake, MN, was Ogimaa-bines, a musical gifted Chippewa spiritual leader."]},{"name":"Byrd","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Bird  ."]},{"name":"Heaney","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Aidan, Malachy, Nuala, Ronan.","Irish:","Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hÉanna</b> and <b>Ó hÉinne</b>, ‘descendant of <i>Éanna</i>’, a very common personal name of uncertain meaning. It was borne by various early Christian saints, most notably Saint Éanna of Aran. The name has been erroneously understood as containing the element <i>éan</i> ‘bird’ and as a result the surname was sometimes Anglicized as   Bird  ."]},{"name":"Blackbird","meanings":["Native American (also <b>Black Bird</b>): translation into English of a personal name such as Lakota Sioux <i>Ziŋtkala Sapa</i>, which is composed of <i>ziŋtkala</i> ‘bird’ and <i>sapa</i> ‘black’. See also   Bird   4.","English (Durham): nickname for someone with a dark beard, from Middle English <i>blak</i> ‘black’ + <i>berd</i> ‘beard’ (Old English <i>blæc</i> + <i>beard</i>)."]},{"name":"Burd","meanings":["English: variant of   Bird  .","Jewish (from Poland and Ukraine): nickname for a man with a notable beard, from a southern Yiddish pronunciation of Yiddish <i>bord</i> ‘beard’."]},{"name":"Burt","meanings":["English (southern): variant of   Bird  ,   Bright  , or   Burd  .","German: Middle High German <i>burt</i> ‘that which is due or proper’, therefore a nickname for someone who has fulfilled his obligations properly.","Jewish (from Poland and Ukraine): variant of   Burd  ."]},{"name":"Hummingbird","meanings":["Native American (Cherokee): translation into English of a personal name based on the Cherokee name <i>walela</i> for a hummingbird. See also   Bird   4."]},{"name":"Heagney","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hÉignigh</b>, ‘descendant of <i>Éigneach</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘forceful’. The spelling of the Irish name was often simplified to <b>Ó hÉinigh</b> and then Anglicized as   Heaney   or ‘translated’ as   Bird  , the latter because of a perceived similarity to <i>éan</i> ‘bird’."]}]},{"name":"Carlton","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, a local name from any of various places (in Beds., Cambs., Co. Durham, Leics., Lincs., Northants, Notts., Suffolk, and Yorks.) named with Old English <i>carl</i> ‘(free) peasant’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’, i.e. ‘settlement of the free peasants’. This is the same name as   Charlton  , <i>Ch-</i> representing the southern (Anglo-Saxon) pronunciation, while <i>C-</i> represents the northern (Anglo-Scandinavian) version."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Hugo","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of   Hugh  , used throughout the Middle Ages in official documents, and now enjoying a revival as a given name."],"variants":[]},{"name":"le","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  ♂ ‘Profit’ or ‘sharp’.","2  ♀, ♂ ‘Upright’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":4,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705183,"age":24,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":34,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":44,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Baron Carlton Hugo le Bird was born before 1062, in Bunbury, Cheshire, England, his father, Carlton Hugo Le Bird, was 51 and his mother, Werburga Dombue, was 51. He married Mrs Carlton Hugo le Bird before 1094, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"before 1062–":"enne 1062–Surnud","1062–Male":"1062–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1094–1157":"1094–1157","1010–1067":"1010–1067","1010–Female":"1010–Surnud","1106":"1106","1157":"1157","1067":"1067","1066":"1066","1010":"1010","before 1062":"enne 1062","1086":"1086","1030":"1030","1096":"1096","1062":"1062","before 1094":"enne 1094","1094":"1094","Haughton, Bunbury Par, Cheshire, England":"Haughton, Cheshire, England","Bunbury, Cheshire, England":"Bunbury, Cheshire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"before 1062–":"ennen vuotta 1062–Kuollut","1062–Male":"1062–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1094–1157":"1094–1157","1010–1067":"1010–1067","1010–Female":"1010–Kuollut","1106":"1106","1157":"1157","1067":"1067","1066":"1066","1010":"1010","before 1062":"ennen vuotta 1062","1086":"1086","1030":"1030","1096":"1096","1062":"1062","before 1094":"ennen vuotta